            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> we'd assume you wanted the old behaviour because of what you assigned it to. In hindsight we possibly should have done the same for `int`\r\n\r\nThe question is whether we'd hide bugs on user side that way. If someone called `main(-3)` above, we'd have to raise a runtime exception, or do something else that would avoid returning an unexpected value from the computation. It's easy to forget that something as ubiquitous and innocent as `int` can trigger an invalid computation on exponentiation.",
